SIMPLE: costard
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Costard
<hw>Cos"tard</hw> <pr>(k?s"t?rd)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Prob. fr. OF.
<ets>coste</ets> rib, side, F. <ets>c⟦ocir⟧te</ets>, and meaning orig.,
a ribbed apple, from the ribs or angles on its sides. See
<er>Coast</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>An apple, large and round like
the head.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Some [apples] consist more of air than water . . . ; others more
of water than wind, as your <qex>costards</qex> and pomewaters.</q>
<rj><qau>Muffett.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The head; -- used contemptuously.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Try whether your <qex>costard</qex> or my bat be the harder.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Costardmonger</ent>⟦br⟧
